ce:section.ce:para:
The singlet oxygen quantum yields (Φ

                           Δ
                        ) give an indication of the potential of complexes as photosensitizers in applications where singlet oxygen is required. It is well accepted that singlet oxygen is the primary cytotoxin in PDT for most photosensitizers. Singlet oxygen quantum yields (ΦΔ) were determined using photochemical methods with 1,3–diphenyl‐2–benzofuran (DPBF) as a singlet oxygen scavenger in DMSO. For all formulations, the Q‐band absorption did not change, suggesting the photostability of both 1 and 1-GQDs-MnO2@PtNPs over the irradiation period (1-GQDs-MnO2@PtNPs used as an example, Fig. S8). However, the absorbance of DPBF decreased over the irradiation period and was used to quantify the singlet oxygen quantum yields (
                        Fig. S8
                        ). There was no degradation of DPBF in the photosensitizer‐free solution (in the absence of 1 or 1-GQDs-MnO2@PtNPs). Table 1 shows that the ΦΔ of 1-GQDs-MnO2@PtNPs is higher than that of 1 or 1-GQDs in DMSO. The superior singlet oxygen quantum yield (Φ

                           Δ
                        ) of 1-GQDs-MnO2@PtNPs (63%) compared to that of 1 (55%) or 1-GQDs (52%) may be credited to the increased spin-orbital coupling effect for metals in the nanoparticles, a known heavy atom effect. The results outlined in Table 1 suggest that in addition to the added functionality of oxygen supplementation through the decomposition of exogenous H2O2, the 1-GQDs-MnO2@PtNPs also possessed higher singlet oxygen-generating ability, an 8% increase from that of 1 alone. Therefore, 1-GQDs-MnO2@PtNPs has potential in photodynamic therapy. Its applicability in PDT is evaluated below.
